Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 87th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
This week was less about any major breakthroughs or exciting product launch=
es, and more about storytelling. Stories are important. We need narratives =
to make sense of things, especially when those things are novel. Luckily,  =
there=E2=80=99s a new brand of storyteller on the internet =E2=80=94 a grou=
p of optimistic narrative-builders covering the most exciting things that t=
he builder-builders are working on. We=E2=80=99ll share some of their work =
below.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1) How to make an old immune system young again [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/07360566-650d-4531-98f2-02432f92f8ce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Heidi Ledford for Nature
Antibodies that target blood stem cells can rejuvenate immune responses in =
mice.
Ohh to be young again! New researched published in Nature this week found t=
hat reducing certain stem cells in old mice can rejuvenate their immune sys=
tems, making them more effective at fighting viral infections and reducing =
inflammation. This works by rebalancing the types of stem cells that affect=
 immune responses, shifting them from those that cause inflammation to thos=
e that support a more youthful immune function. We=E2=80=99re still years a=
way from going from mice to men, but the research=E2=80=99s findings could =
help improve aging immune systems.=20
The more and more I learn about all of the new research in human biology an=
d longevity, the more and more I think my goal (and everybody=E2=80=99s goa=
l) should just be to not die in the next 20 years. If you just make it anot=
her 20 years, my bet is that we=E2=80=99ll hit some longevity escape veloci=
ty and you=E2=80=99ll be living an extra 50 healthy years than you otherwis=
e would. Bryan Johnson might actually be right=E2=80=A6just don=E2=80=99t d=
ie.=20
(2) The Future of Humanity's Energy No One Knows About | Terraform [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/bd1a1ef7-4272-4167-bfe3-83a62df3c4b9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
You may remember the name Casey Handmer. We=E2=80=99ve written about him a =
few times, but usually in the context of the Vesuvius Challenge. Last summe=
r, Casey was the first participant to find substantial, convincing evidence=
 of ink within the unopened scrolls. This was a crucial discovery that ulti=
mately helped a trio of young researcher actually read parts of the ancient=
 scrolls and win the Vesuvius Challenge. Well, for Casey, the Challenge was=
 very much a side hustle. His main hustle is being the founder of Terraform=
 Industries.
Terraform, according to Casey, scrubs CO2 from the atmosphere and uses rene=
wable hydrogen to convert it to natural gas, more cheaply than drilling, fr=
acking, and piping. Terraform is positioned to scale as rapidly as falling =
solar electricity prices allow, and aims to displace the majority of fossil=
 hydrocarbon production by 2035.
Those are ambitious goals and a short paragraph isn=E2=80=99t going to do t=
he company justice. But Jason Carman=E2=80=99s 20 minute deep dive on Casey=
 and Terraform does the trick. Casey is one of those founders that makes yo=
u both dumbfounded that people this smart exist and thankful that people th=
is smart exist.
I hope Packy writes a deep dive on this company some day soon.
(3) Underground Hyperlogistics Delivery Drones | Garrett McCurrach, Pipedre=
am [ https://substack.com/redirect/917b694f-bcc8-450c-b30e-a423e647a467?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Speaking of ambitious founders taking on SciFi challenges=E2=80=A6we=E2=80=
=99ve got Garrett from Pipedream. Pipedream is a hyperlogistics company tha=
t aims to deliver (basically) anything in under 10 minutes for less than $1=
=2E Imagine a miniaturized underground=20=
subway system connecting our homes and=
 offices with stores, restaurants, and delivery hubs. Pipedream is building=
 that.
That plan is almost laughably ambitious. And Garrett has faced the laughers=
 and doubters. But he=E2=80=99s come out on the other side with more legiti=
mate business traction results than really any one could have imaged. The s=
ystem is already being deployed is Peachtree Corners, a city northeast of A=
tlanta, and the company is currently cutting deals with some of the most sc=
aled restaurants chains and grocery stores in the country.
If you want a look into what the future of delivery will look like, watch t=
hat video.
(4) Cancer: A Food-Borne Illness [ https://substack.com/redirect/741d57ae-f=
4a9-43cb-a931-484c96eb3529?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
A video heavy week here at the Weekly Dose.=20
For better or worse, this video is not embeddable in Substack because it=E2=
=80=99s only available on X [ https://substack.com/redirect/f42adef6-518c-4=
ae2-92fa-63a0ed409bed?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. According to Grace Price, the 18 year old filmmaker behind=
 the video, that=E2=80=99s because X =E2=80=9Cis only on this platform that=
 I am able to release a film that challenges big food conglomerates and mai=
nstream health claims without fear of censorship.=E2=80=9D
Price=E2=80=99s documentary is a 24 minute expos=C3=A9 of the U.S. food sys=
tem and its links to cancer. More accurately, it=E2=80=99s an exploration o=
f food and epigenetics. Epigenetics is the study of how behaviors and envir=
onment can cause changes that affect the way genes work, without altering t=
he DNA sequence itself. According to Price, the way we eat is epigentically=
 altering our genes and increasing cancer rates.
She=E2=80=99s probably right. The issue, however, is not most folks reading=
 this don=E2=80=99t know that eating shitty food leads to higher cancer rat=
es =E2=80=94 I think that=E2=80=99s pretty well accepted at this point =E2=
=80=94 but that the systems, incentives, and realities of our current food =
system have made it incredibly hard to bring about the scaled change we=E2=
=80=99d need to actually yield societal level results.
There are two approaches here. Tops down =E2=80=94 something like regulatio=
n demanding certain nutritional thresholds =E2=80=94 or bottoms up =E2=80=
=94 something like changing the hearts and minds of the populace such that =
demand for shitty foods goes down and healthy foods go up. We=E2=80=99re mo=
re partial to demand-side incentives here, and videos like Grace=E2=80=99s =
(which at the time of writing had 2M views within 14 hours) should help in =
moving the needle there.
(5) Nuclear Loan [ https://substack.com/redirect/6bc6bb8d-84d8-4a7f-8285-63=
ae1c146652?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] + Coal-Fired Shutdowns [ https://substack.com/redirect/64104646-2963-4=
516-8815-f589cc99a33e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
A nice little duo of energy stories from the Gray Lady this week.=20
On Wednesday, the Biden Administration approved a $1.5B loan guarantee that=
 will allow Holtec International to revive its Palisades nuclear plant. Whe=
n it=E2=80=99s open, the Palisades will be the first re-opened nuclear powe=
r plant in U.S. history. This is a very strong signal from the White House =
that it=E2=80=99s committed to supporting nuclear revitalization and expans=
ion.
Also on Wednesday, an agreement was reached between a number of environment=
al groups and Granite Shore Power to shut down the last two coal-fired powe=
r plants in New England over the coming years. Coal still accounted for 17%=
 of total electricity produced in the U.S. in 2023, but it=E2=80=99s share =
of total is dropping precipitously. Companies who still do have operational=
 plants are now rolling out transitions to cleaner, renewable energies.
Not a bad Wednesday. I=E2=80=99d trade two coal-fired power plants for a ne=
wly re-opened nuclear plant any day of the week.
Bonus: Boom Supersonic Announces Successful Flight of XB-1 Demonstrator Air=
craft [ https://substack.com/redirect/ab3e83bd-a74f-48dc-a236-f2c513c7a7ae?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Last week, Boom Supersonic [ https://substack.com/redirect/f5e0eb54-a67e-4e=
b0-83d6-4dccd6d438fd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] announced the successful flight of XB-1 [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/fb5c1a77-580c-49c8-8491-a4ba44130b45?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the world's first independently=
 developed supersonic jet. This was a major milestone on bringing back supe=
rsonic travel (RIP Concorde).=20
Look out for an essay from Packy next week on what the future of flight mig=
ht look like=E2=80=A6
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox early next week.=20
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

